summary.seg: This manuscript contains different collections of sermons, including the Sermones de Tempore by Jacobus de Voragine, 'Sermones de Mortuis', and 'Sermones de Sanctis'. On its flyleaves at the beginning and end are administrative notes and medical recipes, largely in the hand of largely of Richard Gosmer, vicar of Basingstoke from 1499-c. 1541

Dr Clarck Drieshen
Project Cataloguer, Curious Cures in Cambridge Libraries
Cambridge University Library

msContents.textLang: Latin, with some additions in Middle English

msItem.title: Administrative notes and medical recipes
msItem.incipit: 1v Memorandum quod exposui pro Johanne Burley ista que fecuntur et pro aliis executoribus
msItem.explicit: 4v Item a lode of tymber the estur weke Item in postys caryyd bifore estur xij lodys of which [...] lode solde
msItem.note: Added in in or after 1509, largely written by Richard Gosmer of Magdalen College, Oxford, Vicar of Basingstoke from 1499-c. 1541.

msItem.title: Tract on the Mass (Officium Matutinale)
msItem.incipit: 4v Nullus insuper sacerdos parochialis id est curam gerens alicuius parochie
msItem.explicit: 4v Hic W. Lynwode utriusque iure doctore in constitucione linthiamina de celebracione missarum
msItem.note: The tract cites Johannes de Friburgo (1250–1314) De Friburgo, Johannes, 1250-1314, Summa Confessorum; William Lyndwood (1375?–1446) Lyndwood, William, 1375?–1446.

msItem.title: Chronica pontificum et imperatorum (extract)
msItem.author: Martinus Polonus
msItem.incipit: 11v In cronisis martini M n Robertus est Karolus rex francie vita et scientia preclarus devotionisque tante floruit
msItem.explicit: 11v Hic fecit sequenciam sancti spiritus assit nobis gracia
msItem.note: Extract on King Robert of France. Added in the 15th century.

msItem.title: On additions to the Mass by various popes
msItem.incipit: 11v Alexander papa constituit aquam aspercionis cum sale benedici et in habitaculis hominum aspergi
msItem.explicit: 12r Terciam missam ipsa honoris diei tercia quando illuxit nobis dies redemptionis nostre
msItem.note: Added in the 15th century, and followed by three notes(e.g. 'Nota: Corpus in templo / ligna in Psalmo / mens in foro / pessime dividitur homo').

msItem.title: Tract on Christ as spouse of the Church
msItem.incipit: 12r Legimus quod dominus nostris ihesus Christus ecclesie sponsus sepcies tenerissime ploravit
msItem.explicit: 12v Sit graciarum actio honor et gloria per omnia saecula saeculorum Amen

msItem.title: De observacione sabbati
msItem.explicit: 12v nec sacramenta id est iuramenta nisi pro pace vel alia necessitate praestentur
msItem.note: Tract featuring extracts from Origen of Alexandria (185–254) Origen, of Alexandria, 185–254, Super librum Numerorum; and Pseudo-Augustine Pseudo-Augustine, Saint, Bishop of Hippo, Sermo in parochiis satis necessarius; added in the 15th century.

msItem.title: Tract on Moses
msItem.incipit: 13r Nota quod moyses profecturus ab egipto versus terram promissionis habuit specialiter tres inimicos
msItem.explicit: 13r Unde Jac. 4 resistite diabolo et fugiet a nobis

msItem.title: Historia ecclesiastica (extract)
msItem.author: Bede the Venerable
msItem.incipit: 13r Beda in de gestis anglorum narrat de Etheldreda virgine uniente omni viro suo xij annis quo defuncto ipsa intravit religionem valde vixit ibidem
msItem.note: Extract on St Etheldreda. Added in the 15th century and followed by two notes, beginning: Nota quod arta est ura and Nota proverbium 19. flagellato pestilente stultus sapientior fiat.

msItem.title: De igne purgatorio
msItem.author: Caesarius of Arles (Pseudo-Augustine)
msItem.rubric: 13v Sermo beati Augustini de igne Purgatorio et de animabus
msItem.incipit: 13v In lectione apostolica que nobis paulo ante recitata est
msItem.explicit: 14v Et elimosinarum largitate possimus redimere . prestante domino nostro ihesu Christo qui cum patre et filio et spiritu sancto viuit et regnat deus per omnia secula seculorum amen
msItem.finalRubric: 14v laus et ihesu dulcedo nomen Explicit
msItem.note: Added in the15th century and followed by a note attributed to Augustine (De die judicij).

msItem.title: Sermones de tempore per annum sive sermones dominicales, Dom. 1 Adv.-Dom. xxv. sermo 3
msItem.author: Jacobus de Voragine
msItem.incipit: 15r Humane labilis vite decursus salubri erudicione nos monet rebus non incumbere perituris
msItem.explicit: 127r Hic actus perfecto erit omnibus sicut ipsa vita erit communis ad illum beatum finem per ducat nos qui est principium et finis qui sine fine viuit et regnat per infinita secula seculorum. Amen
msItem.finalRubric: 127r Istum librum scripsit Willelmus de Eglisfehan deo gracias Qui scripsit scribat semper cum numine viuat

msItem.title: Sermones de mortuis
msItem.incipit: 129r Revertatur pulvis in terram suam et spiritus redeat ad deum qui dedit illum Ecclesiastes xii. 7 videlicet. Cuilibet peregrino in arena manenti

msItem.note: A collection of 26 sermons numbered with rubricated Roman numerals.

msItem.title: Untitled sermon
msItem.incipit: 136r A finibus terre laudes audivimus gloriam iusti
msItem.explicit: 136r carnem eum crucifigendo cum viciis et concupiscentiis

msItem.title: A diagram of the division of the world (T-O map)
msItem.incipit: 136r Tres filii Noe post diluvium diviserunt orbem in tres partes
msItem.explicit: 136r In affrica libia Penpatis ethiopia Licana Bizancia Jeculia Siata Anuda Samaria Circes maiores et minores

msItem.title: Sermones de sanctis
msItem.author: Jacobus de Voragine
msItem.incipit: 137r Vestigia eius secutus est pes meus viam eius custodivi
msItem.explicit: 256v tanquam medium per quem conservantur omnia ut sic verificetur quod ait Apostolus: Ro. 6. et in ipso et per ipsum et in ipso sunt omnia ipsi honor et gloria in secula seculorum
msItem.note: Sermons on ff. 172v-185r and ff. 196v-209r break off and begin imperfectly due to missing quires and folios. The sermon on f. 234v ends imperfectly because the text has been left unfinished, with a column and a quarter left blank.

msItem.title: Miracle of the Virgin Mary concerning a virgin named Murieldis
Miracle about a beautiful tree found inside a hole in the ground
msItem.incipit: 257r In libro quodam reperitur quod quidam ab unicorne fatigatus incidit in foream maximam
msItem.explicit: 257r sine dubio in lacum mixe inter crudelissimas feras cademus causa patre nostro in foneam

msItem.title: Administrative notes and medical recipes
msItem.note: Drafts for indentures and testaments, payments, recipes for making wafers, dated to 1501-1505, largely written by Richard Gosmer of Magdalen College, Oxford, Vicar of Basingstoke from 1499-c. 1541.

msItem.title: Quaestiones super vetus testamentum
msItem.author: Isidore of Seville
msItem.incipit: 257v Contra hunc serpentem clamat Apostolus cum dicit: metuo ne sicut serpens evam seduxit
msItem.explicit: 257r Framea vero versatilis posita ad custodiendam viam ligni vitae temporales pene intelliguntur

foliation.p: Mid-20th-century foliation in Arabic numerals written in pencil in the right outer corners of rectos.
foliation.note: Numbering in pencil in the upper right-hand corner of the rectos, by H.L. PinkPink, H. L..
Folio numbers 173-184, 197-208, 260-263 assigned to leaves no longer present in the volume (as per historic foliation practice at Cambridge University Library).

list.item: Quire 712-2+2 (ff. 73-84: the 5th and 6th leaves, after f. 76, cancelled as indicated by stubs; 2 singletons with binding stubs inserted after f. 77)
Quire 1912-1 (ff. 227-237: the 10th leaf, after f. 235, cancelled as indicated by a stub)
Quire 224-2 (ff. 254-255: the 3rd and 4th leaves, after f. 255, cancelled as indicated by stubs)
Quire 234+2-2 (ff. 256-259: 3rd and 4th leaves, after f. 259, excised as indicated by stubs, 2 medieval parchment endleaves added after f. 257)

collation.formula: 112 214 34 4-612 712-2+2 (5th and 6th cancelled, 2 leaves inserted) 810 912 1010 1112 128 13-1712 186 1912-1 (10th cancelled) 204 2112 224-2 (3rd and 4th cancelled) 234+2-2 (3rd and 4th excised, 2 leaves added)

signatures.p: Leaf signatures combining Roman numerals with letters 'a' and 'b' in quires 2 and 7 respectively.
Arabic numbers in brown ink ('2'-'5', '7'-'10', and '1s'-'3s', '5s', '7s'-'12s') at the centres of the lower margins of the first rectos of quires 3-6, 8-11, 13-15, 16, 17-22.

catchwords.seg: Horizontal catchwords in the hand of the scribe placed in frames of brown ink in the lower margins below the second columns of the last versos of quires.

collation.note: This collation deviates from that provided by M.R. James and H.L. Pink in that it considers ff. 3-14 - a quire that was added at a later stage - as Quire 1 instead of Quire b ('a' consists of two flyleaves at the beginning: ff. 1-2). Moreover, whereas James and Pink attribute numbers to the missing quires between ff. 172-195 ('Quire 15') and ff. 196-209 ('Quire 17') this collation only attributes numbers to quires that are present in the manuscript. Consequently, the quire numbers in this record do not match with those that Pink has written in pencil in the lower-right hand corners of the first rectos of quires, (except Quire 16, which is the quire that consists of folios 185-208 both in this record and the collations by James and Pink).

supportDesc.condition: The manuscript contains a few added organic materials: a dried blade of grass in the gutter between f. 137v and f. 138r; and a fly that was found on f. 231r that is now enclosed in a melinex folder (see insect) and kept separately with the manuscript in a grey conservation box.

layout.seg: Ruled in leadpoint, frame and line, in 2 columns, 52 lines to page, written below top line.

handNote.p: Folios 15r-28v and ff. 73r-84v were copied by a single hand working in a Gothica Cursiva Libraria script.

Folios 29r-72v and ff. 85r-256v were copied by a single hand working in a Gothica Hybrida Libraria script, a 'Willelmus de Eglisfehan'(?) according to the colophon on f. 127r (repeated without his name on f. 256v).
The added notes on ff. 1v-4v and ff. 257r-259r are written in cursive scripts with Secretary and Anglicana, largey by the hand of Richard Gosmer (d. 1547), and can be dated to c. 1500-1510.

The added text on the Mass on f. 4v, the alphabetical index on ff. 5r-11v and subsequent texts on ff. 11v-14v are written by 15th-century hands in cursive scripts with both Secretary and Anglicana features.
The text accompanying the T-O map on f. 136r and two miracles on f. 219r are possibly written by the same hand in an Anglicana script of the 14th century.
The text by Isidore of Seville on f. 219v is written in an Anglicana script from the 14th century.

decoNote.p: A circular diagram representing the world, divided in four quarters representing Asia, Paradisus, Europa, and Affrica (f. 136r).
One six-line puzzle initial in blue and red (f. 15r).
Three-line blue initials in frameworks of red penwork decoration with pen-flourishing in red (ff. 5r-11v).
Two-line initials in red or blue with penwork decoration and pen-flourishing in the opposite colour (ff. 29r-72v and 85r-256v).
Titles and marginal headings rubricated in red ink (ff. 15r-256v).
Paraphs alternately in red and blue ink.
One-line capitals highlighted in red, underlining in red, and paraphs in red (ff. 5r-13r).

binding.p: Brown half leather with marbled paper sides over card boards.

provenance.p: Richard Gosmer (d. 1547) Gosmer, Richard, d. 1547 of Magdalen College, Oxford, and vicar of Basingstoke (1499-c 1541): his ownership is indicated by a secundo folio reference at the top of on f. 1v: Ricardus Gosmer, 2a fo. libenter.
John Wateregge (fl. c. 1500-c. 1550) Wateregge, John, fl. c. 1500-c. 1550 of Winslade near Basingstoke: his name inscribed on f.1v.
Thomas Browne (fl. 16th century) Browne, Thomas, fl. 16th century: his ownership inscription on f.5r: Liber sermonum in membranis vel pellibus Thomas Brouneus possessoris huius.
John Moore (1646-1714), bishop of Ely Moore, John, 1646-1714 : no. 463 (f. 1r) in Bernard, Catalogi librorum manuscriptorum Angliæ et Hiberniæ (c. 1697), Volume 2 Part 1, p. 373 (no. 9649).

history.acquisition: Presented to the University Library in 1715 by George I George I, King of Great Britain, 1660-1727 : donation bookplate engraved by John Pine Pine, John, 1690-1756 in 1736 on the inside cover.

recordHist.source: This catalogue entry draws on an unpublished description of the manuscript composed between 1926 and 1930 by M.R. James James, M.R. (Montague Rhodes), 1862-1936, now held in the University Archives (UA ULIB 7/3/74) and an unpublished description of the manuscript composed between 1948 and 1970 by H.L. PinkPink, H. L., now held in the University Archives (UA ULIB 7/3/75).
